Fitbit & ET Glasses - Methods

Initial Preparations

Run following Code if and only if new data is added to the initial data.

ET Glasses

Acceleration

The Tobii Glases record acceleration data with a frequency of 100Hz. Therefore it should be possible to calculate the walked distance wearing the glasses using the following formulas:

\[\Delta x_{d,i} = 0.5 (t_{i-1}-t_{i})^2, \text{ with }i=2,...,t_n; d = z,x\]

\[x_d=\sum_{i=1}^n |\Delta x_{d,i}|, \text{ with }i=2,...,t_n; d = z,x\]

\[\sum x=\sqrt{x_z^2+x_x^2}\]

Using these formulas, one brave assumption must be made, that is, for every time period the initial velocity is equal to 0.

The real data gives plausible values.

On the contrary, simulated situations revealed multiple problems.

For the first simulation the participant was standing still without moving its head and with strong movements of the head respectively. A reliable measurement would give the same distance for both situations. Afterwards, we simulated two two times 5 meter long walks. One time the participant turned around after 5 meters. During the other walk the participant walked 5 meters and walked back backwards. Again, we expect the glasses to give the same walking distance. To test real world situations we simulated two random walks in a simulated class room. One walk simulated an extensive walk and the other walk simulated a less intense walk. Additionally, we tested the values for taking the elevator and walking a staircase. The simulated situations give the following values.

Plotting the acceleration reveals the problems with the acceleration data.
